**Summary:**

| Bug | Line | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| Off-by-one | `i <= items.length` | `items[3]` → `undefined`, then `.name` throws | `i < items.length` |
| Null element | `items[i].name` | `items[2]` is `null` | Guard with `item && item.name` |

## Root Causes

There are **two bugs** in this code:

1. **Off-by-one error** (line 2): `i <= items.length` causes the loop to access `items[3]` on the final iteration, which is `undefined`. Reading `undefined.name` throws the error you see.
2. **Null element** (line 10): `data[2]` is `null`, so even with the correct loop bound, `items[2].name` would throw `Cannot read properties of null (reading 'name')`.

## Minimal Fix

```diff
 function processItems(items) {
-  for (let i = 0; i <= items.length; i++) {
-    if (items[i].name.length > 3) {
-      console.log(items[i].name);
+  for (const item of items) {
+    if (item?.name?.length > 3) {
+      console.log(item.name);
     }
   }
 }
```

**What changed:**
- `for...of` replaces the index loop — no off-by-one risk, no out-of-bounds access.
- Optional chaining (`?.`) guards against `null`/`undefined` items and items missing a `name` property.

If you prefer keeping the index loop for some reason, the minimal fix would be `<` instead of `<=` plus a null check inside the loop — but `for...of` + optional chaining is cleaner and equivalent.

